{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Generation Methods",
      "simpleDefinition": "The various ways electricity is produced from energy sources such as fossil fuels, renewables, or nuclear power.",
      "anchor": "The 'starting point' of the electrical supply chain where energy is converted into electricity.",
      "misconception": "Believing that all electricity is produced by a single source type rather than a diverse mix of methods."
    },
    {
      "term": "Transmission Voltages",
      "simpleDefinition": "Extremely high voltages used to move electricity efficiently over long distances across the national grid.",
      "anchor": "The 'motorway' levels of the grid: 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV.",
      "misconception": "Confusing these high-level transmission voltages with lower-level distribution voltages like 11 kV or 33 kV."
    },
    {
      "term": "kV (Kilovolt)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A unit of electrical pressure equal to 1,000 Volts.",
      "anchor": "1 kV = 1,000 V; used to describe high-voltage systems.",
      "misconception": "Treating 'kV' as the same as 'V', which leads to a 1,000-fold error in understanding the electrical pressure present."
    },
    {
      "term": "Micro-generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "Small-scale production of electricity, often by individual households or small businesses.",
      "anchor": "Domestic solar panels or small-scale wind turbines on a single building.",
      "misconception": "Thinking micro-generation refers to large-scale utility power stations."
    },
    {
      "term": "Photovoltaic (PV)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A method of generating electricity directly from sunlight using solar cells.",
      "anchor": "Solar PV panels found on roofs or in solar farms.",
      "misconception": "Believing PV panels require heat to work, when they actually require light (photons)."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Transmission voltages in the UK are 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV.",
    "Generation is the conversion of primary energy into electrical energy.",
    "High voltage is used for transmission to minimize energy loss over long distances.",
    "The generation mix includes fossil fuels, renewables, and nuclear power."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Mixing up transmission voltages (132kV+) with distribution voltages (33kV and below).",
    "Assuming all generation methods are large-scale power stations.",
    "Underestimating the magnitude of a kilovolt (kV) compared to a standard volt (V)."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Generation Methods",
      "objective": "Identify the primary methods used to generate electricity for distribution.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Electricity generation is the starting point of the supply chain, where primary energy is converted into electrical energy. To maintain a reliable grid, the UK uses a diverse mix of generation methods. Large-scale power stations typically utilize fossil fuels—specifically coal, oil, and gas—or nuclear power to produce bulk electricity.",
        "Alongside these, renewable energy sources are increasingly vital. These include wind, wave, hydro, and biomass. Photovoltaic (PV) generation is another key method, using solar cells to convert light directly into electricity. While many of these operate on a utility scale, we also see micro-generation.",
        "Micro-generation refers to small-scale production, such as domestic solar panels or small wind turbines located at the point of use. Whether it is a massive nuclear facility or a small-scale PV installation, these various methods provide the energy that enters the national network for distribution. You must be able to identify this full range of sources, from traditional fossil fuels to modern renewable technologies."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the full list of sources: coal, oil, gas, nuclear, wind, wave, hydro, biomass, photovoltaic, and micro-generation."
    },
    {
      "title": "Transmission Voltages",
      "objective": "Identify the specific high voltages used in the UK transmission network.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "After electricity is generated, it must be transported across long distances via the national grid. This stage is known as transmission. To move large amounts of power efficiently and reduce energy losses, the electricity is stepped up to very high pressures called transmission voltages. You can think of the transmission network as the 'motorway' of the electrical system.",
        "In the UK, you must identify three specific transmission voltages: 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV. It is essential to remember that 'kV' stands for kilovolt, meaning 1,000 Volts. For example, 400 kV is 400,000 Volts. These high-voltage levels are strictly used for transmission and are distinct from the lower voltages used in local distribution.",
        "Understanding these specific values—132, 275, and 400 kV—is fundamental for identifying which part of the supply chain you are dealing with. When you see large pylons and massive substations connecting different regions, they are operating at these specific transmission levels to ensure bulk power reaches regional centers effectively."
      ],
      "hint": "The three transmission voltages are 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV. Remember that 1 kV equals 1,000 Volts."
    }
  ]
}

