{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "National Grid Integration Task",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between various generation methods and the specific high-voltage levels required for national transmission.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To understand the UK supply chain, you must link the source of power to its transport method. Generation is the starting point where energy is converted, whether through traditional fossil fuels like gas or modern renewables like photovoltaic systems.",
      "Once generated, this power doesn't stay local if it's intended for the national grid; it enters the transmission 'motorway'. This requires stepping the voltage up to specific high-voltage levels to ensure it can travel hundreds of miles with minimal loss."
    ],
    "questionText": "A new energy project involves a large-scale 'Biomass' plant and a 'Hydro' electric station. Explain what stage of the supply chain these facilities represent and identify the three specific voltage levels (in kV) they would use to transmit this power across the national grid.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The facilities (Biomass and Hydro) represent the 'Generation' stage of the supply chain.",
      "The three specific UK transmission voltages are 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV.",
      "The use of 'kV' (kilovolts) signifies the high pressure required for long-distance transmission efficiency."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about the technical term for the 'starting point' of the chain and recall the three highest voltage levels taught in this lesson."
  }
}

